post_text: After receiving an update about the possibility of continued power outages across our area along with internet instability, Conroe ISD will now be closed on Friday, August 28. We look forward to resuming Remote/Online Instruction on Monday, August 31, and welcoming PPCD, PreK, K, and 1st grade students back to their campuses for In-Person Instruction. We will also welcome 2nd-12th grade students whose last names begin with A-C back to their campuses as detailed in the Back-to-School Schedule on the Conroe ISD website.

post_text: To allow families time to prepare for and address any potential impact to our region from Hurricane Laura, all Conroe ISD campuses and offices will be closed on Wednesday, August 26, and Thursday, August 27. There will be no Remote/Online or In-Person Instruction during this time, and all extracurricular activities have been canceled. The District will communicate instructional plans for Friday, August 28, after assessing the storm’s impact on Thursday. Updates will be posted on www.conroeisd.net as well as our social media pages. Messages will also be sent via CISD’s mass communication system. Please stay safe!

The District will communicate instructional plans for Friday, August 28, after assessing the storm’s impact on Thursday. Updates will be posted on www.conroeisd.net as well as our social media pages. Messages will also be sent via CISD’s mass communication system. Please stay safe!

post_text: The Student World Affairs Council (SWAC) of Greater Houston has awarded Caney Creek High School, Conroe ISD the "SWAC of the Year 2020." The mission of SWAC is to promote understanding of the world – its people, politics, economies and cultures – to enable the Houston community to participate more effectively in the global world. Caney Creek represented the largest SWAC chapter in the Houston Area and is among the most geographically distant.

post_text: Students from College Park High School, Conroe ISD's Destination Imagination (DI) team, The Timekeepers, won first place in the DI Global Finals 2020 Virtual Tournament. The team was given a prompt to create a skit in which two characters work together to accomplish a goal. The Timekeepers project, created entirely via Zoom, involved a unique storyline that fit the category yet was still out-of-the-box innovative. Check out their winning skit here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YtgGuphp8Mg&feature=youtu.be

post_text:
Beginning Thursday, August 13, curbside meals will no longer be free for all students. Breakfast and lunch meals will be available curbside for students to purchase or free to students who qualify.
- Families are asked to pick up/purchase meals for all of their -children at the campus of their oldest child.
- Meals will be available curbside at all campuses on Tuesdays and Thursdays from 10 AM – 12 PM.
- Multiple meals will be distributed at a time.
- Tuesday: 2 breakfast meals/2 lunch meals
- Thursday: 3 breakfast meals/3 lunch meals
- A student meal card must be presented to scan and identify the student when meals are picked up.
- This card is located in Parent Access and can be printed on paper or presented electronically on a phone.
- Any change from a cash transaction will be applied to the student’s meal account.
- Pre-payments can be made at www.myschoolbucks.com.
- Meal prices and the free and reduced meal application are available on the Child Nutrition website.
(*This process may be updated.)

Questions? Please contact the Child Nutrition Department at (936) 709-8185.

post_text:
As we begin our journey to the first day of school, there are many details to share about all students starting school on August 12th in Remote/Online Instruction. Beginning the week of August 3rd, families will receive regular updates via our mass notification system on topics including accessing online instructional materials, first day attendance and daily check-in requirements, school meals, and technology resources. These updates will also include informational videos on how to login and navigate the learning management systems, Canvas and Seesaw. Please be on the lookout for communication from your student's school or teacher about the 2020-2021 school year!

We look forward to another great year in Conroe ISD!

post_text: Congratulations to Owen Plourde and Raphaela De Marchi Padovanis, students at McCullough Junior High, Conroe ISD, for receiving the 2020 1st Place National Winner on their ExploraVision project! The ExploraVision competition for K-12 students engages the next generation in real world problem solving with a strong emphasis on STEM. ExploraVision challenges students envision and communicate new technology 20 years in the future through collaborative brainstorming and research of current science and technology. Their project placed 1st in the 7th-9th grade category and was selected from over 5,000 entries.

post_text: Conroe ISD is continuing to monitor the ever evolving status of COVID-19 in our community and is working closely with our local health authorities. We are aware of the presumptive positive case in Montgomery County as well as other confirmed positive cases in the greater Houston area. While students are not in class, the District continues to work to limit the spread of illness. In addition to the routine daily cleaning at our facilities, each campus is being deep cleaned with e-mist electrostatic sprayers as part of our five to seven day rotation in place since the beginning of February. All cleaning materials used by the District are known to fight COVID-19 as well as other illnesses. We will continue to learn more about COVID-19's presence in our community in the coming days and will send another update Friday afternoon. Updates will also be posted on our COVID-19 webpage: conroeisd.net/department/health-services/2019-novel-coronavirus/

post_text:
FACT: The Census Bureau is bound by Title 13 of the U.S. Code to keep your information confidential.

Under Title 13, the Census Bureau cannot release any identifiable information about you, your home, or your business, even to law enforcement agencies. The law ensures that your private data is protected and that your answers cannot be used against you by any government agency or court.

The answers you provide are used only to produce statistics. You are kept anonymous: The Census Bureau is not permitted to publicly release your responses in any way that could identify you or anyone else in your home.

Every person counts! #2020Census

FACT: The Census Bureau is bound by Title 13 of the U.S. Code to keep your information confidential.

Under Title 13, the Census Bureau cannot release any identifiable information about you, your home, or your business, even to law enforcement agencies. The law ensures that your private data is protected and that your answers cannot be used against you by any government agency or court.

The answers you provide are used only to produce statistics. You are kept anonymous: The Census Bureau is not permitted to publicly release your responses in any way that could identify you or anyone else in your home.

Every person counts! #2020Census

post_text:
Beginning in March, The U.S. Census Bureau will invite households across the country to participate in the #2020Census.

You might ask, what is the Census?

Simply put, the Census is a head count of every person in the United States. To be sure the government represents the people, the U.S. Constitution requires a population count every 10 years. Your response helps guide planning for the future of our community and help inform decisions on how billions of dollars are allocated annually for critical public services like roads, schools, hospitals and healthcare clinics, fire and emergency response services, and hundreds of other programs. By law, all census responses are completely confidential and your personal information can not be shared with any law enforcement agencies. Every person counts no matter who you are or where you live!

Learn more at https://2020census.gov/.

post_text:
In January 2020, Conroe ISD will begin utilizing the Purposity app. This app allows community members to receive weekly notifications about students and families in need, and purchase items that are shipped directly to the student’s school. In order to post these items, the district needs 250 members to download and follow Conroe ISD through the app under the 'Organizations' tab. All donations are tax deductible and donors will receive a tax receipt from Purposity at the end of the calendar year. Please visit https://www.purposity.com/faqs for more information.

For questions please contact Lynda Gowin at lgowin@conroeisd.net,or Christina Ramos at cramos@conroeisd.net.

The Health Fair provides valuable information to our employees and their families about available healthcare providers and wellness related services in our community.

If you would like to participate as a 2020 Conroe ISD Employee Health Fair exhibitor, please complete and submit the online registration form by Friday, December 6, 2019.

For more information, please visit https://www.conroeisd.net/department/hr/employee-health-fair/.

All Conroe Independent School District campuses and offices will be open on Monday, Sept. 23, except for Caney Creek High School, Conroe ISD. Caney Creek High School will be closed for repairs on Monday, but is planned to open on Tuesday, Sept. 24.

Tonight’s varsity football games will take place as scheduled. Campuses will communicate about any other planned events.
text:
All Conroe Independent School District campuses and offices will be open on Monday, Sept. 23, except for Caney Creek High School, Conroe ISD. Caney Creek High School will be closed for repairs on Monday, but is planned to open on Tuesday, Sept. 24.

Tonight’s varsity football games will take place as scheduled. Campuses will communicate about any other planned events.

post_text: All Conroe ISD campuses and offices will be closed on Friday, September 20, to allow roads to continue clearing, impacted facilities to be cleaned, and time for families to recover. High school extra-curricular events scheduled for Friday evening have not been canceled. A decision will be made by noon on Friday regarding these activities.
text: All Conroe ISD campuses and offices will be closed on Friday, September 20, to allow roads to continue clearing, impacted facilities to be cleaned, and time for families to recover. High school extra-curricular events scheduled for Friday evening have not been canceled. A decision will be made by noon on Friday regarding these activities.

post_text: All after-school activities and evening events at Conroe ISD facilities for Thursday, Sept. 19, are cancelled.
text: All after-school activities and evening events at Conroe ISD facilities for Thursday, Sept. 19, are cancelled.

post_text: Due to deteriorating road conditions and multiple power outages, Conroe ISD will be closed today, Thursday, Sept. 19. Students who have already been picked up by buses will be taken to their school and held there until they can be safely dismissed.
text: Due to deteriorating road conditions and multiple power outages, Conroe ISD will be closed today, Thursday, Sept. 19. Students who have already been picked up by buses will be taken to their school and held there until they can be safely dismissed.

post_text: Conroe ISD is in close contact with local authorities and monitoring the weather and roadways. Any updates will be posted on www.conroeisd.net as well as our social media pages. Messages will also be sent via phone, email, and text through CISD’s communication system. Parents and employees wanting to receive messages via text should make sure they have opted-in by texting “Y” to 67587.
